Here is an example of a C++ function which will read a specified.txt file line-by-line and count how many times a certain string appears within it. This could be used for anything from grepping logs or code, to simply counting how often you mention pizza in your diary! 
The following should work as long as the std::ifstream library is available where this code is implemented.
```c++
#include <fstream>
#include <string>
#include <iostream>

std::string line; //String to hold each individual line of input
int counter = 0;    //Counter variable, defaulted to zero
const int MAX_LINE_LENGTH = 512;      //Maximum length of any one line (arbitrarily set here)
bool foundIt = false;              //Flag if we find our search term yet

//Function prototype for searching through text file "file" and returning count when done
int getCount(std::string file);

/*Main execution point, called automatically after preprocessor completes*/
int main() {
	std::cout << "Searching \"pizza\" in file...\n";
	getCount("foodlog.txt");       //Call function with appropriate arguments
	return 0;
}

/*Recursive function for reading in lines of data until end of file reached*/
void loadLine(std::istream& streamIn, const std::string& filename, bool& foundTerm, int& totalCount){
	while (!foundTerm &&!streamIn.eof()) { //While we haven't found our target & not at EOF
		std::getline(streamIn, line);        //Read next line into line
		for (size_t pos = line.find("pizza"); pos!= std::string::npos; pos = line.find("pizza", pos)) {   //Scan every occurrence of "pizza" on current line
            ++totalCount;                         //Increment overall count whenever we see a match
		}
		foundTerm |= streamIn.peek() == '\n';     //Set flag whether newline character seen
	}
}

//Function to do actual searching in file and return value back to caller
int getCount(std::string file) {
    std::ifstream myFileStream;           //Create input file object using desired file name
    bool found = false;          //Used later so we can display whether or not our term was actually found anywhere in file
    int count = 0;               //Variable to store result of finding term once loop finishes executing

    myFileStream.open(file);            //Open up desired file for reading

    if (myFileStream.is_open()) {  //Check if opening succeeded before continuing - handle errors accordingly
        std::string line;             //Declare empty string to hold contents of single line
        while (loadLine(myFileStream, file, found, count)) {     //Loop while more data available
            ;                                                //Do nothing but keep looping over lines
        }
    } else {
        std::cerr << "\nError opening file '" + file + "'." << "\n";  //Display error message about failed opening attempt
    }
    myFileStream.close();                         //Close input file once finished reading/writing
    return count;                                  //Return final tally to calling function
}```

Here is an implementation of the binary search algorithm: 

def bin_search(arr, x):
    if len(arr) == 0 or arr[0] > x:
        return -1 # not found

    left = int((len(arr)-1)/2)
    right = len(arr) - left - 1
    mid = (left + right) // 2
    if arr[mid] == x:
        return mid

    if arr[mid] < x:
        return bin_search(arr[:mid], x)
    else:
        return bin_search(arr[mid+1::], x)

In this function, we check if the length of the array is zero or if the first element of the array is greater than the searched value `x`. If so, we immediately return `-1` indicating that the element was not found. 

Next, we set two variables `left` and `right` which hold indices for our initial partitioning of the array into two subarrays. We then use `(left + right)` / 2 to calculate the index of the middle element of these two partitions. 

We compare the middle element with `x`, if they are equal, we found it! Otherwise, we recurse on either the left side or the right side depending on whether the middle element is less than or greater than `x`. In each recursive call, we halve the size of the remaining search space until eventually the element is found or the remaining search space becomes empty.

